# OCEN Platform — Role-Based User Guide

**Last updated:** 12 Jul 2026 · Covers the platform as of the `dpdp-compliance-analysis` merge and {{PRODUCT_NAME}} brand rollout.

This guide explains the platform from the perspective of everyone who touches it: the **vendor/borrower**, the **anchor**, the **lender**, the **ops team**, and **platform admins**. If you only need a technical overview, see [`userguide.md`](userguide.md); this document is organized by *who you are* and *what you do*.

---

## 0. One-Paragraph Overview (Read This First)

A vendor (small manufacturer/supplier) sells goods to a large anchor (auto-ancillary or manufacturing corporate) and holds an unpaid invoice. Instead of waiting 60–90 days to get paid, the vendor applies for a loan against that invoice through this platform. The platform validates that the invoice is real and that the anchor has confirmed it owes the money (**Kind 1 attestation**), checks the vendor has enough financial data on file, computes risk indicators, matches the vendor to eligible lenders, and submits the application over **OCEN 4.0** (India's open lending network). Lenders independently decide whether to approve and at what rate — that decision is never made by this platform. Once approved, money disburses to the vendor and repayment routes directly from the anchor to the lender.

| Role | One-line summary |
|---|---|
| **Borrower / Vendor MSME** | Applies for a loan against a confirmed invoice; gets paid early. |
| **Anchor MSME** | The buyer whose GST-portal invoice acceptance is what makes the loan financeable. Passive role — no platform login needed. |
| **Lender** | An NBFC/bank on the OCEN network that receives pre-screened applications and makes the actual credit decision (D4). |
| **Ops team** | Platform staff who onboard vendors/anchors, monitor applications, and intervene (hold/flag/escalate) via the {{BACK_OFFICE_NAME}}. |
| **Admin** | Platform-admin role — manages users/roles, DPDP compliance, breach response, decision rules, and branding. |

---

## 1. Borrower / Vendor MSME

### Who you are
A small or medium manufacturer/supplier (an MSME, typically in the Kolhapur auto-ancillary belt) who has sold goods to a large anchor company and is waiting on an invoice.

### Getting an account

There are two ways to get onto the platform:

**A. Self-registration** (you initiate it)
```
POST /vendors/register
{
  "name": "Your Company Name",
  "gstin": "27AADCB2230M1ZT",      # 15-char GST number
  "phone": "+919876543210",
  "udyam_number": "UDYAM-XX-00-0000000",   # optional
  "udyam_category": "micro"                 # optional
}
→ { "vendor_id": "<uuid>", "status": "active" }
```
You're active immediately — no waiting on ops approval.

**B. Ops-invited** (the platform's ops/anchor-relationship team invites you)
1. Ops sends you an invite link (generated via their back-office).
2. You open the link and complete:
```
POST /vendors/activate
{ "invite_token": "<token from the link>", "name": "...", "udyam_number": "..." }
→ { "vendor_id": "<uuid>", "status": "active" }
```

### Before you can apply: your invoice needs to be "Kind 1"

This is the single most important concept for you. The platform will not send your loan application to any lender unless your invoice is **Kind 1 attested** — meaning all of the following are true:

| Condition | What it means for you |
|---|---|
| Valid IRN | Your invoice has a valid Invoice Reference Number from the GST e-invoicing portal (a 64-character hash). This is generated automatically when you raise a proper e-invoice. |
| IMS accepted | The anchor has explicitly **accepted** your invoice on their GST Invoice Management System (IMS). "Deemed accepted" (anchor took no action) counts as a weaker signal — your application can still proceed but is flagged, which may mean a smaller pool of eligible lenders or less favorable terms. |
| Repayment routing active | The anchor has enabled a confirmed repayment channel — this is what convinces lenders that money will actually flow back. |

**Practical implication:** chase the anchor to *actively accept* your invoice on GST IMS rather than letting it sit as "pending." A pending or rejected invoice means your Kind 1 check fails outright and you cannot apply.

### Applying for a loan

```
POST /loans/apply
{
  "invoice_id": "<uuid>",
  "vendor_gstin": "27AADCB2230M1ZT",
  "anchor_gstin": "36AABCY9234H1Z5",
  "amount_requested": "500000.00",
  "idempotency_key": "optional-dedup-key"
}
→ { "application_id": "<uuid>", "status": "initiated", "current_gate": "d0_kind1", "workflow_id": "..." }
```

### What happens after you apply — the full journey

Your application moves through a sequence of checks (the platform calls these "decision gates"). You can poll status anytime:

```
POST /loans/status
{ "application_id": "<uuid>" }
→ { "status": "...", "current_gate": "...", "amount_sanctioned": ..., "lender_id": ... }
```

| Step | What's checked | If it fails, you'll see |
|---|---|---|
| **0. Consent check** | You must have granted consent for your data to be used for loan origination and Kind 1 attestation. | "Consent required for loan processing" — re-grant consent and reapply. |
| **1. D0 — Kind 1 gate** | IRN valid + IMS accepted + repayment routing active + your GSTIN active. | "Invoice not attested. Ensure buyer accepted on GST IMS." |
| **2. Account Aggregator data fetch** | You (or your bank, via the AA framework) must approve a data-sharing consent so the platform can pull 6 months of bank statements and GST returns. This can take a few minutes if you need to approve it live; times out after 10 minutes. | "Financial data fetch failed. Please approve Account Aggregator consent." |
| **3. D1 — Data sufficiency** | Needs ≥6 months of financial data, no older than 30 days, with GST returns filed. 3–5 months (fresher than 60 days) is accepted but flagged as "marginal" — you may see smaller offers or higher rates. Fewer than 3 months, stale data (>60 days), or unfiled GST returns fails outright. | "Insufficient financial data. Please have at least 3–6 months of bank statements and GST filings." |
| **4. D2 — Derived attributes** | The platform computes metrics like Days Sales Outstanding (DSO), buyer concentration, invoice dilution rate, and the anchor's payment punctuality. This step never blocks you — it only attaches informational flags that lenders see when pricing your loan (e.g., depending too much on one buyer, or that buyer paying late historically, can mean a higher rate). | N/A — always passes through. |
| **5. D3 — Lender pre-screen** | The platform matches your profile (loan amount, months of data, risk flags, trust score) against each lender's published eligibility filters. If zero lenders match, you're rejected here. | "No lenders currently match your profile. Improve GST filing or reduce risk indicators." |
| **6. (Rare) Ops hold** | Ops staff can pause your application for manual review (e.g., a fraud check) for up to 72 hours. | Status shows "held" with a reason; contact ops if it's been a while. |
| **7. OCEN submission** | Your application (now including invoice proof, GST/bank data, and risk indicators — never your login credentials) is cryptographically signed and sent to every matched lender simultaneously. | — |
| **8. D4 — Lender's decision** | Each lender independently runs their own credit assessment. This is **not** something this platform controls — every lender's internal criteria differ. Lenders typically respond within minutes to a few hours; the platform waits up to 24 hours. | "Lender declined. You can retry with a different lender." or a timeout message. |
| **9. Offer received** | You'll see the approved amount, interest rate, tenor, processing fee, and a Key Fact Statement (KFS) link. | — |

### Why the process is designed this way

The platform never makes the actual lending decision (D4) — that's always the lender's, both for regulatory reasons and because we don't want to encode any single lender's credit policy. What the platform *does* guarantee is that by the time your application reaches a lender, it's backed by structural proof the receivable is real — which is why approvals tend to be faster and rates tend to be better than approaching a lender cold.

### Quick reference: your endpoints

| Endpoint | Method | Auth | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| `/vendors/register` | POST | None | Self-register |
| `/vendors/activate` | POST | None | Activate from an ops invite |
| `/loans/apply` | POST | None | Submit a loan application |
| `/loans/status` | POST | None | Check application status |
| `/dpdp/consent/{data_principal_id}` | GET | Admin-only (see §5) | Check your own consent status (via ops/admin) |

