## 4. Ops Team

### Who you are
Platform operations staff working day-to-day in the {{BACK_OFFICE_NAME}} (and occasionally calling the platform API directly) to onboard vendors/anchors and monitor/intervene on loan applications.

### Your two roles

| Role | You can do |
|---|---|
| **`operations`** | Hold / release / flag / escalate applications; list and view all applications (read). |
| **`anchor-manager`** | Invite vendors, onboard anchors; list and view applications (read). |

(`platform-admin` can do everything either role can, plus compliance/user-management tasks — see §5.)

### Where you work

Primarily **{{BACK_OFFICE_NAME}}** (`http://13.234.12.74`, site `ocen.local`), themed with the {{PRODUCT_NAME}} brand. Every meaningful platform event — new applications, decisions evaluated, offers, disbursements, ops actions — is forwarded there in near real time via a webhook bridge (`backoffice_sync` service), so you don't need to poll the platform API for routine monitoring.

### Onboarding a vendor

```
POST /ops/vendor/invite   (Bearer token; anchor-manager or platform-admin)
{
  "name": "Vendor Name",
  "gstin": "27AADCB2230M1ZT",
  "phone": "+919876543210",
  "udyam_number": "UDYAM-...",   # optional
  "invited_by": "you@company.com"
}
→ { "vendor_id": "<uuid>", "invite_token": "...", "invite_link": "https://.../invite/<token>" }
```
Send the `invite_link` to the vendor; they complete registration themselves via `/vendors/activate`.

### Onboarding an anchor

```
POST /ops/anchor/onboard   (Bearer token; anchor-manager or platform-admin)
{ "name": "...", "gstin": "...", "sector": "...", "region": "...", "onboarded_by": "you@company.com" }
→ { "anchor_id": "<uuid>", "status": "onboarded" }
```

### Application monitoring and intervention

```
GET  /ops/applications/active               # all non-terminal applications
GET  /ops/applications/{application_id}     # full detail: gate, status, offer, flags
```

**Hold** an application before it's submitted to lenders (e.g., pending a manual fraud check):
```
POST /ops/hold
{ "application_id": "<uuid>", "reason": "Manual review — suspicious activity", "held_by": "you@company.com" }
```
This pauses the Temporal workflow via a signal. If not released within **72 hours**, the application automatically rejects with `ops_hold_expired`.

**Release** the hold once you've cleared it:
```
POST /ops/release
{ "application_id": "<uuid>", "released_by": "you@company.com" }
```

**Flag** an application (non-blocking annotation, e.g. "priority" or "manual_review"):
```
POST /ops/flag
{ "application_id": "<uuid>", "flag_type": "suspicious", "note": "...", "flagged_by": "you@company.com" }
```

**Escalate to collections** (post-disbursement, e.g. an overdue loan):
```
POST /ops/escalate
{ "application_id": "<uuid>", "reason": "Loan 90 days overdue", "escalated_by": "you@company.com" }
```

### A typical day

1. **Morning:** review new applications in the {{BACK_OFFICE_NAME}} dashboard (populated automatically from platform webhooks).
2. **Triage:** flag anything unusual; hold applications that need manual verification.
3. **Onboarding queue:** invite vendors and onboard anchors as sales/relationship requests come in.
4. **Post-disbursement:** watch for overdue repayments and escalate to collections when needed.

### Every action you take is auditable

Every ops command (hold, release, flag, escalate) emits an event to the platform's event stream and is visible in the audit trail — there's no silent override of the decision pipeline.

